# Quickstart {#quickstart .content-title .mb-0}

**LocalAI** is a free, open-source alternative to OpenAI (Anthropic,
etc.), functioning as a drop-in replacement REST API for local
inferencing. It allows you to run
[LLMs](../../features/text-generation/index.html), generate images, and
produce audio, all locally or on-premises with consumer-grade hardware,
supporting multiple model families and architectures.

üí°

**Security considerations**

If you are exposing LocalAI remotely, make sure you protect the API
endpoints adequately with a mechanism which allows to protect from the
incoming traffic or alternatively, run LocalAI with `API_KEY` to gate
the access with an API key. The API key guarantees a total access to the
features (there is no role separation), and it is to be considered as
likely as an admin role.

To access the WebUI with an API_KEY, browser extensions such as
[Requestly![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)](https://requestly.com/){rel="external"
target="_blank"} can be used (see also
[https://github.com/mudler/LocalAI/issues/2227#issuecomment-2093333752)![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)](https://github.com/mudler/LocalAI/issues/2227#issuecomment-2093333752)){rel="external"
target="_blank"}. See also [API
flags](../../advanced/index.html#api-flags) for the flags / options
available when starting LocalAI.

## Using the Bash Installer [*link*](index.html#using-the-bash-installer){.anchor aria-hidden="true"} {#using-the-bash-installer}

Install LocalAI easily using the bash installer with the following
command:

``` {#26e307f .language-sh}
  curl https://localai.io/install.sh | sh
  
```

For a full list of options, refer to the [Installer
Options](https://localai.io/docs/advanced/installer/){bs-delay="{\"hide\":300,\"show\":550}"
bs-html="true"
bs-title="<a href='/docs/advanced/installer/'><p>ADVANCED</p><strong>Installer options</strong><br></a>"
bs-toggle="tooltip"} documentation.

Binaries can also be [manually
downloaded](https://localai.io/docs/reference/binaries/){bs-delay="{\"hide\":300,\"show\":550}"
bs-html="true"
bs-title="<a href='/docs/reference/binaries/'><p>REFERENCES</p><strong>LocalAI binaries</strong><br></a>"
bs-toggle="tooltip"}.

## Using Homebrew on MacOS [*link*](index.html#using-homebrew-on-macos){.anchor aria-hidden="true"} {#using-homebrew-on-macos}

‚ö†Ô∏è

The Homebrew formula currently doesn't have the same options than the
bash script

You can install Homebrew's
[LocalAI![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)](https://formulae.brew.sh/formula/localai){rel="external"
target="_blank"} with the following command:

``` {#7621983 .language-}
  brew install localai
  
```

## Using Container Images or Kubernetes [*link*](index.html#using-container-images-or-kubernetes){.anchor aria-hidden="true"} {#using-container-images-or-kubernetes}

LocalAI is available as a container image compatible with various
container engines such as Docker, Podman, and Kubernetes. Container
images are published on
[quay.io![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)](https://quay.io/repository/go-skynet/local-ai?tab=tags&tag=latest){rel="external"
target="_blank"} and [Docker
Hub![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)](https://hub.docker.com/r/localai/localai){rel="external"
target="_blank"}.

For detailed instructions, see [Using container
images](../container/index.html). For Kubernetes deployment, see [Run
with Kubernetes](../kubernetes/index.html).

## Running LocalAI with All-in-One (AIO) Images [*link*](index.html#running-localai-with-all-in-one-aio-images){.anchor aria-hidden="true"} {#running-localai-with-all-in-one-aio-images}

> *Already have a model file? Skip to [Run models
> manually](https://localai.io/docs/getting-started/models/){bs-delay="{\"hide\":300,\"show\":550}"
> bs-html="true"
> bs-title="<a href='/docs/getting-started/models/'><p>GETTING STARTED</p><strong>Install and Run Models</strong><br></a>"
> bs-toggle="tooltip"}*.

LocalAI's All-in-One (AIO) images are pre-configured with a set of
models and backends to fully leverage almost all the features of
LocalAI. If pre-configured models are not required, you can use the
standard [images](../container/index.html).

These images are available for both CPU and GPU environments. AIO images
are designed for ease of use and require no additional configuration.

It is recommended to use AIO images if you prefer not to configure the
models manually or via the web interface. For running specific models,
refer to the [manual
method](https://localai.io/docs/getting-started/models/){bs-delay="{\"hide\":300,\"show\":550}"
bs-html="true"
bs-title="<a href='/docs/getting-started/models/'><p>GETTING STARTED</p><strong>Install and Run Models</strong><br></a>"
bs-toggle="tooltip"}.

The AIO images come pre-configured with the following features:

-   Text to Speech (TTS)
-   Speech to Text
-   Function calling
-   Large Language Models (LLM) for text generation
-   Image generation
-   Embedding server

For instructions on using AIO images, see [Using container
images](../container/index.html#all-in-one-images).
